Demetrius On Style: The so-ealled epiphoneme may be defined as a phrase which adds adornment, and it is supreme as an elevator of style. It should be remembered that a phrase either aids the sense or adorus it. For instance, the sense is aided by such a phrase as ‘ Like the hyaeinth' etc. while it is adorned by the words which follow, ‘ and it still blooms’ etc. The addition thus made to the foregoing sentence is clearly an adornment or embellishment. . . . In general the epiphoneme is like the shows or displays of the rich, such as the cornices and triglyphs of their houses and

the purple borders of their robeS. For it is essentially a mark of wealth in words.
